sentence: Technically, the DJIA closed last week a hair's breadth below the 12,400 level, but bullish aspirations for a continued rally appear dashed this morning.
Look for the DJIA to potentially test support in the 12,300 region, with an additional backstop near the 12,250 region - which is home to the Dow's rising 10-day moving average.
The SPX, meanwhile, is facing resistance near 1,345, though it is more likely that the broad-market index will pressure support in the 1,330 region this morning.
The SPX's 10-day moving average is hovering just below 1,330, and could provide additional support for the index.
In equities news, Wal-Mart Stores Inc. ( WMT ) reported a fourth-quarter profit of $6.06 billion, or $1.70 per share, as sales rose 2.5% to $115.6 billion.
Excluding items, Wal-Mart said it earned $1.34 per share.
Analysts were expecting a profit of $1.31 per share on sales of $117.5 billion.
Looking ahead, WMT said it expects first-quarter earnings of 91 cents to 96 cents per share, and full-year earnings of $4.35 to $4.50 per share.
Wall Street is currently expecting a first-quarter profit of 96 cents per share and a full-year profit of $4.45 per share.
Elsewhere, The Home Depot Inc. ( HD ) said that its fourth-quarter profit spiked 72% over the same quarter last year to $587 million, or 36 cents per share.
Sales rose to $15.13 billion from $14.57 billion a year ago.
Wall Street was expecting a profit of 31 cents per share on revenue of $14.81 billion.
The company also announced that its board has raised its quarterly dividend 6% to 25 cents a share, payable March 24 to holders of record March 10.
For fiscal 2012, Home Depot forecast earnings from continuing operations to rise 9.5% from 2011 to $2.20 per share, with sales up 2.5%.
Finally, Hormel Foods Corp. ( HRL ) said that its first-quarter net profit rose 33% to $148.83 million, or 55 cents per share.
Net sales rose to $1.9 billion from $1.7 billion in the year-ago period.
Analysts were looking for earnings of 43 cents per share on sales of $1.86 billion.
The company also lifted its full-year guidance range to $1.62 to $1.68 per share from $1.55 to $1.60 per share.
On the earnings front, Hewlett-Packard ( HPQ ), RadioShack ( RSH ), and Macy's (M) are slated to release their quarterly earnings reports.
Keep your browser at SchaeffersResearch.com for more news as it breaks.
On the economic front, the S&P Case-Shiller home price index for December, the consumer confidence index for February, and the latest Richmond Fed business activity survey are on tap for today.
Tomorrow offers up the ICSC-Goldman Sachs chain store sales index, as well as existing home sales data for January.
On Thursday, the government's weekly report on crude supplies will hit the Street a day late, due to Monday's holiday.
Traders will also receive their regularly scheduled update on weekly jobless claims.

Finally, we round out the week with a pair of key economic reports: the preliminary estimate on fourth-quarter gross domestic product (GDP), and February's consumer sentiment index from Reuters/University of Michigan.
Equity option activity on the Chicago Board Options Exchange (CBOE) saw 1,837,991 call contracts traded on Friday, compared to 1,139,099 put contracts.
The resultant single-session put/call ratio arrived at 0.62, while the 21-day moving average held at 0.56.
**The volume data shown above is from the Nasdaq and NYSE exchanges only.
It does not include regional volume activity, which means that other daily volume quotes you see may be higher.

Overseas trading looks abysmal this morning, as all 10 of the foreign indexes that we track are in negative territory.
The cumulative average return on the collective stands at a loss of 1.31%.
Growing turmoil and political tensions in the Middle East, including this weekend's violent protests in Libya, sent nervous investors scrambling to the sidelines in Asian trading.
What's more, Japanese stocks took a nosedive after Moody's Investors Services lowered the country's ratings outlook.
Fear has also spread into European trading, where soaring crude prices have contributed to the session's turmoil.
The U.S. dollar is struggling to hold above breakeven this morning, with the U.S. Dollar Index up 0.06% at 77.74 in electronic trading.
Commodities, however, have rocketed higher following news of violent protests in Libya.
In fact, crude futures have soared some $6.75 to $96.46 per barrel in premarket trading.
Meanwhile, gold futures are also headed higher due to the Middle East turmoil, rising $8.40 to $1,397 an ounce in London.
